Thank you for sharing your thoughts about this, Eli! I know that a horror series will obviously contain potentially triggering content. And I think trigger warnings will be important to include! I know TMA did ones for each episode. But there’s another level here - that some horror media uses trauma for flavor without commentary. I trust the Toons to not use such a basic and reductive story telling device (they’re playing 4d chess when they plan their comics! 😂), but I also know that not everyone is aware of the TTI, so it’s a really important point to bring up!

Tara (Toonimated)

04/02/2023 at 00:04:00 PDT

First of all, I'm so sorry that you had to go through something so traumatic. It's not something anyone should have to experience and it's really commendable for you to bring it up so we can be more aware and respectful of the topic. We don't want anyone to feel unsafe or be made uncomfortable in any real, unpleasant ways - only in fun ones! 🙂 Having your question to guide us is incredibly helpful. That way we can write in a way that is as sensitive to everyone's emotional well-being as possible I'll try to give you as much of an answer as I can based on what we have planned for the story so far. Hopefully that will be safe enough to do, but please take care while reading just in case. As we are currently imagining PINTV, it's mostly a survival horror with the focus of the story being the fear of losing one's mind, what is real and what is not, and does it even matter if what you're afraid of becomes real anyway? It will primarily take place in a psychiatric hospital or ward and although there will be some exploration of the mental health system, that's not the focus. You can probably think of it a bit like the SCP foundation or the Magnus Institute in that the main cast are all employed there and there are some good people trying to do the right thing, and there are some selfish people and some corrupt people and shitty systems and bad practices in place, etc. Most of the patients are there voluntarily for treatment. However, some may be checked in by caregivers or sent there through the justice system - that's not super fleshed out yet. On top of that, there will be a paranormal situation going on - this part of the story is more like a dark fantasy/horror, the hospital itself becomes something of a nightmare realm with a situation that might be a bit like Squid Games in that there will be more of a game-like situation where they fight against an evil force. There will probably be some things that would warrant a trigger warning in the story (like needing to medicate someone, characters experiencing mental breakdowns, use of restraints by faceless-ikea-employee type monster doctors , etc). However, it's important to note that these elements are intended to be unsettling and scary so definitely not intended as a positive example of those types of practices. I hope that I was able to answer your question a little bit, but please let me know if there's something I could further clarify and I will do my best. Thanks again for bringing it to our attention!

Hey everybody, just thought I'd share this snippet of something I've been working on 😄 details will probably change but... just establishing some ✨ideas✨: > "I'll look into it immediately," Kogan had said after the fifth person had called his office to complain about loud noise coming from the second floor. Kogan radioed the members of the security team, but they all informed him that they were still tied up with other matters, so he decided to look into it himself as it had become apparent that nothing would get done until it was resolved. > > Kogan's polished shoes clicked against the grimy tiles as he strode down the 2nd floor hallway, trying to ignore the stench of cigarette smoke and rancid food that hung in the air. He passed a group of six people clogging the hallway outside one of the rooms, smoking, swigging from bottles of beer, and laughing raucously. > > "There's no loitering in the hallways," Kogan said in his most authoritative voice, "Please take your gathering inside or disperse." > > "Who're you?" one of them slurred, eyeing Kogan with open defiance. > > "The property manager," Kogan replied, his jaw set. "Now, please, disperse." > > "Buzz off," another spat, flicking ashes from his cigarette onto the floor at Kogan's feet. Kogan's eyes narrowed as a few gray flecks landed on his polished shoe. A ripple of laughter spread through the small crowd and Kogan felt a flare of anger but he kept it in check; the smallest of the group in front of him had at least 4 inches and 20 pounds advantage over Kogan, so escalating the situation would do him no good – a lesson he'd learned the hard way enough times in his past. > > "You're causing a disturbance," he said, keeping his tone professional, "Disperse or I'll send security." > > Kogan had walked away, ignoring the rest of their laughter and jeers. Not 10 minutes after he'd returned to his office, he received another noise complaint. Kogan radioed his security team again, no answers. Where was everyone? After ten minutes of searching, he finally spotted the officer they called "Wolf" on the first floor, leaning against the wall with his radio hanging from his belt and having what looked like a casual conversation with a tenant. Balling his fists and gritting his teeth, Kogan stalked angrily towards them, but as he drew near, he saw Wolf slip the guy a wad of cash in exchange for a small plastic bag full of little white pills. Kogan felt his blood pressure rise as his mind reeled from the shock of what he'd just witnessed. > > "Excuse me!" Kogan barked, striding towards the pair with purpose. Both men jumped, their eyes wide with surprise. > > Upon laying eyes on Kogan, Wolf seemed to relax again and he let out a small chuckle. Kogan stiffened, glaring daggers at Wolf. > > Wolf addressed the scabby man beside him, saying "Hey, Lenny, have you met our new property manager?" > > The man named Lenny only responded with a nervous smile and wave at Kogan. He looked ready to bolt. Kogan didn't take his eyes off Wolf, his gaze harsh and unyielding. > > "I've been trying to call you for over an hour." Kogan ground out between clenched teeth. "Do you mind explaining what's going on here?" > > Wolf laughed easily, as though Kogan had only caught him having coffee with a friend. "Lenny and I have a deal," he drawled. "I look out for him, and in return he gives me a discount. If you want us to cut you in, just say the word—" > > "You're fired." Kogan snapped, cutting the man off mid-sentence. > > Wolf's face flushed and contorted in a mixture of shock and outrage that might have been comical if not for the circumstance. > > "Who the hell do you think you are?!" Wolf spat at last, "I've been working here for years!" > > "And as of today, you are no longer employed," Kogan replied, his voice steady despite the rage simmering beneath the surface. "Now, get out."

> "Fine!" the officer shouted, shoving past Kogan and knocking him into the wall with a scowl. "11, 12, 13..." Kogan counted under his breath as the last members of their dwindling group passed through the door before he slammed it shut behind them. The echo reverberated ominously through a room much larger than it should have been and Kogan turned to see that they stood not in the lobby as planned, but in a parking garage that couldn't have been there; it was out of place, out of shape, an architectural impossibility that stretched infinitely in all directions. Cars clung unnaturally to the walls and ceiling, their metallic underbellies glinting in the sickly light that bled through the cavernous structure like some mad imitation of an M.C. Escher painting. The survivors pressed in around him, a chorus of frightened voices rising in a cacophony of fear and accusations. "What's happening, Kogan?" "I thought you knew where we were going!" "Are we lost?" "What's taking so long!?" "Just... give me a moment," Kogan hedged, feeling the weight of their fear-laden gazes on him. These people had come to rely on him for guidance and, until now, he had been leading their ragtag group through this labyrinth of nightmares with near unerring precision. But he hadn't foreseen this, and that was what unsettled him the most. The anxiety of the group was contagious, gnawing at the edges of his own fears, but he strove to maintain an air of calm. Every second they spent pondering their next move was another step closer to being swallowed by the sinister shadow that followed them. Up until this point, Kogan had made a point of only consulting the journal when he was alone, but he didn't have that luxury now. Retreating a step and angling his back to the crowd, Kogan pulled his journal from its hiding place. The chatter died down as the collective gaze of the group fell on him. The survivors stared in open confusion as Kogan appeared to be choosing to engage in some self-indulgent journaling while they all awaited their doom. No one had any idea where Kogan found the wisdom to guide them, but Kogan had no doubt that if they did, their judgement of him would certainly be harsher than whatever they were imagining about him at that moment. "Fucking hell, Kogan, have you lost your damn mind?!" A voice broke through the whimpering of the group, causing Kogan to flinch and look up. It was Malcolm, one of the security officers and Kogan's most vocal critic. There had been a palpable tension between them ever since Kogan fired Malcolm’s old friend, Wolf, back when Kogan had first started his job at the apartments, before everything had gone wrong and necessity had forced them into an uneasy alliance. Malcolm glared at Kogan with thinly veiled contempt,"You're going to get us all killed, you asshole!" Malcolm's rage was having an infectious influence on the rest of the small crowd, their voices becoming louder and more hostile as they advanced toward Kogan. "Back off," Oliver’s voice rang out as he came to stand between Kogan and the accusatory stares. "He's doing his best!"

08:58:53

"I don't give a shit!" Malcolm snarled, "Five of us have died while he was 'doing his best'!" Murmured assent rippled through the crowd as fear and resentment began to fill their eyes. "We'd all be dead it wasn't for him," Oliver countered, "If you want to try your luck out there on your own, go ahead! Nobody's stopping you." A flicker of gratitude sparked in Kogan's chest, but it was quickly extinguished by a wave of cold dread as he began to hastily scribble out the events of the day on the next blank page of his journal. His mind was only half on the task as he waited for what came next. Kogan held his breath and silently prayed that no one would question him, that no one would try to see. Because then they would catch him staring at blank pages and surely come to the conclusion that they were being shepherded by a mad man. Kogan's hand slowed to a stop when the golden glow of words not-yet-written began to take shape for his eyes only to see. Messages from a version of himself who had managed to make it through another day and share his account of how he'd done it. This was his curse, his lifeline, his secret weapon. Finally, the shining ink appeared in full and Kogan's breath caught in his throat. A singular word had been scrawled in an angry, accusatory hand that was not his own. "FREAK" Kogan's fingers shook while he flipped through page after page, seeing the derisive word written on every last one, leaving no space for any future entries. The blood drained from Kogan's face, a feeling of ice spread from his chest and outwards to his extremities. He felt dizzy. He wasn't breathing enough, he thought, or maybe he was breathing too much, he couldn't tell. All he could think about was that, in the next 24 hours, someone was going to discover his secret and they would vandalize his journal, rendering it useless and destroying their only hope of survival. And here they were, cornered and facing imminent subjugation to indescribable terror, and he was powerless to prevent it. There was no guidance to be had. There never would be again. He was going to die. Kogan's pulse roared in his ears, the tight knot of panic coiling in his stomach as he looked up at the people before him, their faces seeming to warp in his mind, concealed malice and hatred seeping out from the cracks in their masks. Only Oliver’s gaze held steady, concern lacing his boyish features, but Kogan hardly registered it through the tunnel of paralyzing terror that he was falling down backwards. And then it came. A sound, or rather, the absolute absence of a sound. A harbinger of the arrival of the void entity that had been chasing them. The metal doors of the garage caved in as inky darkness bled forth towards them, an impenetrable gloom so thick that it drowned out all five of their senses. The last thing Kogan saw before his world disappeared was Oliver's outstretched hand and a flash of the terrified and desperate expression on his face. Then everything was drowned out by the oppressive dark. If only Kogan's reaction time had been a little faster... if only he hadn't been weighed down by shame and fear in those last seconds of freedom. Then, at least he wouldn't have been all alone now, lost in an endless sea of nothing but the sharp edges of a word etched in his mind - "FREAK".

Kogan stumbled through the ruinous maze, pain ricocheting through his torn body with every labored step. The metallic taste of blood filled his mouth and his cheeks bore the stinging testament of flesh torn and stretched beyond human capacity before being snapped back. He had been prepared to die, resigned to let the nightmare claim him, and claim him it had, but it had not taken his life. Instead, Kogan feared, it had turned him into something more — and so much less — than human. Wandering alone, the solitude he'd once yearned for felt as hollow and chilling as a tomb. Without the journal, without his fellow survivors, despair curled in his chest and he found himself yearning for the steady gaze of hazel eyes, the reassuring presence of his friend. His eyes stung and his vision blurred with tears as he thought of Oliver... would he ever see him again? Would he have the chance to apologize...? In his heart, he already knew the answer. All he'd known, all he'd relied on, was lost. He had no idea what he was even moving towards anymore. Was it a vague hope of survival? Redemption? Would it not be easier just to lay down and wait for death to find him? Just as his thoughts began to weigh him down, a shadow fell over him and a massive figure stepped out into the hallway, blocking Kogan's path. Kogan stilled, his gaze meeting the grotesque behemoth looming above him. Kogan recognized the creature immediately. It had only been a day or two since he and his fellow survivors had faced this beast, though it already felt like a lifetime ago. Its hide was still lacerated and bleeding from their violent clash that had claimed the lives of three people. But now, Kogan found himself void of the primal terror that had consumed him then. As the creature lowered its monstrous maw and foul breath wafted from its rows of teeth, Kogan welcomed the inevitable embrace of death. But death, once again, did not come. Instead, the beast grunted and stared inscrutably at Kogan. Kogan's breath caught as he stared back into the creature's many eyes and felt an understanding pass between them. Finally, the colossal creature inclined its head and limped away, leaving Kogan's path unobstructed, and his mind reeling. Kogan pressed his eyes closed and bowed his head in resignation. He had been seen and accepted, not as prey, but as a fellow monster — wounded and dying alone — and had been shown mercy. He had no idea how to go forward, but it was clear to him now that there was no going back.

They were huddled in the ruined remains of someone's once cozy living room. Kogan held his shirt out of the way while Oliver cleaned and bandaged his wounds with efficient, practiced fingers despite their meager medical supplies. Kogan did his best to stifle his pitiful sounds through gritted teeth. Closing his eyes only seemed to bring the pain into sharper focus, so he allowed his gaze to roam, landing on various spots around the rook only to dart away from the harsh and nauseating details of their surroundings, until they came to rest at last on the gentle face of his caregiver. Oliver was focused, his jaw set with determination. But under his stoic facade, Kogan could see the tension lurking in those normally jovial eyes; a grim reminder that this was their new reality - injured, hurting, afraid. Alive, though. At least for now. "Does it hurt a lot?" Oliver asked, his voice barely more than a whisper. “I've had worse,” Kogan replied, offering Oliver a weak smile. They both knew it was a lie, but it hung unchallenged in the damp, heavy air. Once Oliver was done, he moved to pack up the first aid kit, but Kogan reached out to catch the younger man’s arm. Oliver flinched, but didn't pull away as Kogan inspected a gash above his elbow. Oliver began to fidget under Kogan's intense scrutiny. "It's fine," Oliver said, attempting a reassuring smile, "it's not that deep." Kogan only frowned, waving for Oliver to pass him the first aid kit and, wordlessly, their roles reversed. As Kogan tried to replicate Oliver's careful ministrations, a stubborn tremor refused to leave his fingers. It wasn't surprising, who could be expected to keep a steady hand given all they'd recently endured? Oliver was the exception. Not too long ago, Kogan had naively believed that Oliver's apparently unshakeable composure was a symptom of plain ignorance. But now he saw it for what it truly was - a honed skill and diligent strength that set Oliver apart from everyone.

20:15:52

Kogan finally finished wrapping the wound, smoothing his fingers over the taped edges and down Oliver's arm. It was a simple gesture, meant to convey comfort, at first... but he found himself lingering, unwilling to break the connection. The small exchange of tenderness had been so profoundly comforting in the midst of all the torment they'd endured, and Kogan didn't feel ready to return to an existence where he couldn't feel the soothing warmth of Oliver's skin or listen to the dependable rhythm of his breathing. Kogan looked up into Oliver's eyes and, for a moment, the world outside their little bubble ceased to exist. Oliver gave him a wan smile, the kind that didn't reach his eyes but made Kogan's heart skip a beat all the same. The tension in the room shifted, the air growing heavier. Then, in a breathless moment, Kogan leaned in. His lips brushed Oliver's. It was soft and beseeching, a plea for comfort he never thought he'd seek, a hesitant touch that was as electrifying as it was terrifying. Then, just as suddenly as the impulse had struck, Kogan retreated, questioning where the sudden boldness had come from. He could see his own shock mirrored in Oliver's eyes. Kogan braced himself for rejection, for mockery. But it never came. On his companion's face, Kogan only read surprise, and, after a moment, understanding. It was Oliver who moved next. His hand cupped the back of Kogan's neck, fingers threading through the tangled hair at his nape. With a gentle self-assuredness that Kogan hadn't expected, Oliver drew him in for a second kiss, this one deeper and full of intention. A wave of relief washed over Kogan. He clutched the front of Oliver's shirt and shut his eyes tight, blocking out their miserable surroundings, the fear, the pain, everything but the pressure and warmth of Oliver's lips on his own. And this... this was what he had been missing, Kogan realized, what he had been denying himself for so long. And now that he had it, he wanted to drown in it. Regretfully, reality was not so accommodating. But even when they eventually parted, and the world came back into focus, it wasn't entirely the same. Now there was a promise that, as long as they had each other, there would be moments of solace to be found amidst the terror, and maybe that could be enough.

Tara (Toonimated)

Kogan finally finished wrapping the wound, smoothing his fingers over the taped edges and down Oliver's arm. It was a simple gesture, meant to convey comfort, at first... but he found himself lingering, unwilling to break the connection. The small exchange of tenderness had been so profoundly comforting in the midst of all the torment they'd endured, and Kogan didn't feel ready to return to an existence where he couldn't feel the soothing warmth of Oliver's skin or listen to the dependable rhythm of his breathing. Kogan looked up into Oliver's eyes and, for a moment, the world outside their little bubble ceased to exist. Oliver gave him a wan smile, the kind that didn't reach his eyes but made Kogan's heart skip a beat all the same. The tension in the room shifted, the air growing heavier. Then, in a breathless moment, Kogan leaned in. His lips brushed Oliver's. It was soft and beseeching, a plea for comfort he never thought he'd seek, a hesitant touch that was as electrifying as it was terrifying. Then, just as suddenly as the impulse had struck, Kogan retreated, questioning where the sudden boldness had come from. He could see his own shock mirrored in Oliver's eyes. Kogan braced himself for rejection, for mockery. But it never came. On his companion's face, Kogan only read surprise, and, after a moment, understanding. It was Oliver who moved next. His hand cupped the back of Kogan's neck, fingers threading through the tangled hair at his nape. With a gentle self-assuredness that Kogan hadn't expected, Oliver drew him in for a second kiss, this one deeper and full of intention. A wave of relief washed over Kogan. He clutched the front of Oliver's shirt and shut his eyes tight, blocking out their miserable surroundings, the fear, the pain, everything but the pressure and warmth of Oliver's lips on his own. And this... this was what he had been missing, Kogan realized, what he had been denying himself for so long. And now that he had it, he wanted to drown in it. Regretfully, reality was not so accommodating. But even when they eventually parted, and the world came back into focus, it wasn't entirely the same. Now there was a promise that, as long as they had each other, there would be moments of solace to be found amidst the terror, and maybe that could be enough.

Yes! We're envisioning that the main story will be shared everywhere and there will be multiple ways to consume it, like Julian said, on different platforms. It'll be the same content, but some will have audio, some will have video, and others will be still images in vertical scroll format. We'll probably do a mixture of prose and illustrations that will capture all of the main story. On our website, though, we'll have the "full" experience with supplemental content to provide some extra food for thought and little clues / mysteries for those who are interested. Basically, we're planning for the universe of this story to be rather large and full of lore and potential for nonlinear side stories just like RoS was, but in this case, we're trying to build in space to share those details and stories along the way in a nonlinear fashion that adds, but is not critical, to the main story.

Tara (Toonimated)

08/06/2023 at 11:40:17 PDT

I think Julian pretty much summed it up, but it’s definitely a situation with a lot of nuance and I feel like we have probably a bit of a different perspective on it than the one most commonly being talked about right now. I think a lot of artists are in a similar boat but keep quiet because we all know it is a sensitive situation and people SHOULD complain and push back so that we get the proper regulations in place, much like when the music industry went through the age of torrenting .mp3s. (that is to say, it will never go back to the way it was before, but it can be better and more fair than it is now.) Bear in mind, a lot of our own artwork was stolen and is part of the database used to train AI Art generators, so we consider ourselves not only concerned bystanders, but actual stakeholders in this debate. Still though, in my opinion, AI is an inevitable step in human progress, and from an objective “look what we as a species have accomplished” standpoint, I think it’s pretty cool. What is not so cool is the socioeconomic system it exists in. New tools have been replacing labor for as long as humans have existed, and it costs jobs but also frees us up to spend less time laboring and more time making the things that that labor can produce. I think we just assumed art was special, but perhaps we are all just really complex meat computers at the end of the day and technology will catch up to all of us in enough time. Basically, I think a lot of the critique of AI and its use should really be turned on capitalism. If people didn’t need to make money on their artwork, or whatever skill they possess, this new tool wouldn’t be perceived as such a doomsday device. That said, I know it’s complicated. I don’t think AI or capitalism are going anywhere soon. The fact is that there really is no such thing as ethical consumerism in capitalism, and AI is no different. But like all things, I think there are ways to do less harm. I feel that we, as artists, are in a unique position in that when we use AI art, it’s only for things that we have the skills to do ourselves. So in that sense, we are not costing anyone a job, we’re only saving ourselves some time. And to Julian’s point, AI art can not be copyrighted so we don’t use it for things that will be monetized. We’ve used it to do a lot of this proof of concept work for PINTV so far, but it won’t be in the final product.

Tara (Toonimated)

08/06/2023 at 13:43:38 PDT

I just want to say thanks as well. We literally couldn’t do any of this without all of your support so we genuinely feel we owe it to you guys to be up front about our process and take your concerns very seriously. It is difficult to talk about this subject with any amount of nuance at the moment, so we appreciate giving us the opportunity to share our perspective and for your openness and understanding as well. We will do our best once we start publishing PINTV to always credit and make clear where we’ve sourced our materials and talent so there is no confusion. 🙂 Also, speaking of art theft, I thought I’d just share sort of a personal anecdote that changed and continues to inform my perspective to this day, which is this: art theft is something that is talked about a lot in the online art community in particular, it’s something that a lot of people are concerned about, and I shared that concern before I started working professionally. However, once I joined the video game industry, I found a lot of the most successful artists in their field were either indifferent or even welcomed “theft” because they saw it as a sign of success. It’s kind of like the same idea as “you know you’ve made it when you start getting haters”, I guess. I’m not even kidding that I’ve met lots of artists who go as far as to post their own art on piracy sites because it gave them more notoriety and made their work seem “in demand”, and it worked for them. I won’t name names, but you probably know some rather successful Webtoon creators who have done this 👀 All this is just to say that sometimes issues like art theft are not so cut and dry. As long as someone isn’t making thousands of dollars on your work by claiming it as their own, sometimes a little notoriety can be a good thing. Who knows how this AI art situation will pan out in the long run, but I suspect it’s possible that the artists whose styles get mimicked the most will actually see the value of their own art increase as people become more aware of its existence and want something original or that AI can’t produce. Kind of on a similar note, something we’ve learned as creators who sell their work is that there are a limited number of people who are willing to pay for anything. For a lot of people, the alternative to getting something for free is not getting it at all so, again, unless someone has found a way to make a lot of money off of your stolen work, chances are that you are not losing much by having it distributed for free. Your odds of getting it in front of people who DO want to pay you just go up, which goes back to the notoriety thing. Adunno, that’s just the lesson I’ve taken away from my experiences so far, for what it’s worth, and in case you want a little more insight into our perspective on that side of the issue 😅💖

i'd recommend starting with the musical - listening to the og broadway version (altho the 2010 version is my personal favorite) and reading a synopsis of each song as you go along. the fandom calls the novel The Brick, and for good reason! it's realllllly long, so it's a) hard to get through the whole thing without being fixated already and b) hard to adapt to a 2 hour musical. it's one of those shows where you zone out for 30 seconds and miss 60 pages of book 😂 (watching the movie might be more accessible/reasonable though, and i definitely recommend it! the singing and javert's acting are. kinda bad. but the rest of the movie is done really well.) i 100% recommend reading/listening to the book at some point tho. it changed me as a person in ways the musical never could. hugo has so much compassion for everyone in the book, even the antagonist (the musical makes him out to be a Villain. he is Not that 2 dimensional. :( ). buuuuut you'd probably want to get some advice on what you can skip. he's famous for looooong dissertations on the paris sewer systems, the battle of waterloo, a side character, Catholicism, etc that aren't relevant to the plot and are really dense (and can make it hard to Get Through it.) so,,yea. tldr: i recommend any version of les mis, most of all the book! but it's probably best to get fixated with the musical soundtrack/movie before trying to get through the book.
